Malicious cyber operations
One widespread form of non-state cyber activity is “[[1]]”. Everything with a clear criminal intention, including ransomware, that is the encryption of a victim’s hard drive to demand ransom or phishing for passwords to commit identity theft, falls into this category. Another form is “[[1]]”, for example an attack against critical infrastructure like a traffic-light system or a nuclear power plant with the aim of causing uncertainty, fear and havoc, usually inflicting physical destruction and human casualties. The probably most harmless form is called “[[1]]”. Examples would be the defacement of government websites, changing text or visual elements, or so-called Distributed Denial of Service attacks, where a website is overwhelmed by a flood of simultaneous server requests, disrupting normal functionality.

Put the stages of the Cyber Kill Chain into the correct order:
[[1]] → [[1]] → [[1]] → [[1]]

Over the last two decades, some severe cyber incidents have become known to the general public. In late April 2007, many {1:MULTICHOICE:=Estonian#OK~Russian#Wrong~Serbian#Wrong} websites, including those of banks and governmental institutions, were flooded with denial-of-service attacks from millions of computers captured in 75 countries for several days. In 2010 security experts discovered a very sophisticated piece of malware, utilizing four previously unknown vulnerabilities as well as stolen security certificates. This software, ‘Stuxnet’, was after something very special: a specific program controlling Siemens industrial hardware to sabotage the {1:MULTICHOICE:North Korean#Wrong~=Iranian#OK~South African#Wrong} nuclear program. In 2015 a group of hackers penetrated the internal net of the {1:MULTICHOICE:US Congress#Wrong~=German Bundestag#OK~Knesset#Wrong}, potentially getting hold of emails and confidential documents

questiontext.text: When it comes to Cyber-operations people often refer to the so-called “attribution problem”. What is this problem referring to (even though the US claims to have solved the problem)?

answer.text: The inability to attribute a successful cyber-defense to one particular soldier, making it impossible to hand out medals for successful cyber-defenders.
The fact that some states turn a blind eye to cyber-activities conducted by a third party from their soil.
The fact that it is potentially impossible to know for sure who was behind an incident.
